				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "Now the customer says\n\nEvery person has a name.\n\nAlmost every OO design immediately adds an instance variable\nWe won't.\n\nInstead we ask a question.\n\nWhy is a name different from an address?\n\nOr\n\neye colour\nsalary\nnationality\nphone number\nVAT number\n\nIt isn't.\n\nThey are all facts about a Party.\n\nThe model is trying to tell us something.\n\nInstead of adding another instance variable every time the customer invents a new fact, we should capture the concept of a fact.\n\nThat concept is the first genuinely important abstraction in the model.\nThe next chapter will derive Observation from failing tests rather than introducing it as an abstract idea. We'll start with a deliberately naive implementation of names, show why it scales poorly, and let the tests motivate replacing fixed attributes with a collection of observations. That is the first major step toward Fowler's Observation pattern and, eventually, the Adaptive Object Model."
			},
			{
				"__type" : "pharoSnippet",
				"children" : {
					"__type" : "snippets",
					"items" : [ ]
				},
				"createEmail" : {
